    featured: true,
    views: 1870,
    content: `<p>The cross-over dribble is one of football's most devastating weapons. When executed correctly, it shifts a defender's weight entirely to one side before exploding past them on the other. It's the move that separates good players from mesmerising ones, and on a five-a-side pitch, it's practically a superpower.</p>

<h2>Understanding the Mechanics</h2>
<p>The beauty of the cross-over lies in its simplicity. You're essentially using one foot to push the ball across your body before accelerating away with the opposite foot. But simplicity in description masks complexity in execution. The timing, the body feint, the change of pace — every element must harmonise perfectly.</p>

<p>Start by approaching the defender at three-quarter speed. This is crucial. If you're already sprinting, you have no extra gear to find. The cross-over demands a burst of acceleration, so you need to hold something in reserve. As you close the gap to about two metres, drop your shoulder slightly to one side. This is your feint — the bait that makes the defender commit.</p>

<h2>The Execution</h2>
<p>As the defender shifts their weight, use the inside of your dominant foot to roll the ball across your body. The key is to keep the ball close. A loose touch kills the move. Simultaneously, plant your standing foot and drive off in the new direction. Your first touch after the cross-over should be with the outside of your opposite foot, pushing the ball into the space the defender has just vacated.</p>

<p>The most common mistake is telegraphing the move. If your eyes are locked on the ball during the cross-over, the defender reads it instantly. Instead, keep your eyes up, scan the pitch, and let the move flow naturally. The best dribblers make it look effortless because they've practiced it thousands of times until it became instinct.</p>

<h2>Drills to Master It</h2>
<p>Set up five cones in a line, spaced two metres apart. Approach each cone as if it's a defender, execute the cross-over, accelerate past, then decelerate before the next cone. Start slow. Build rhythm. Then add speed. Within weeks, the cross-over will feel as natural as walking — and infinitely more satisfying when you leave a defender rooted to the spot on match day.</p>`
