    views: 2890,
    content: `<p>The growth of women's football is no longer a story about potential — it's a story about power. Record attendances, million-dollar broadcast deals, and a generation of young girls who now see professional football as a viable dream. The barriers haven't just been pushed — they've been demolished.</p>

<h2>A History of Exclusion</h2>
<p>To understand the magnitude of today's achievements, we must acknowledge the injustice of yesterday. In 1921, the English Football Association banned women from playing on FA-affiliated pitches. The ban lasted 50 years. Half a century of talent suppressed, dreams denied, and potential squandered by institutional prejudice. When the ban was finally lifted in 1971, women's football had to rebuild from nothing.</p>

<p>The rebuild has been nothing short of extraordinary. The 2023 Women's World Cup drew over two billion viewers globally. The NWSL, WSL, and Liga F are attracting world-class talent and serious investment. Barcelona Femení regularly fills the Camp Nou. These aren't novelty achievements — they're the new normal.</p>

<h2>The South African Story</h2>
<p>In South Africa, Banyana Banyana's journey mirrors the broader narrative. Their 2022 AFCON triumph was a watershed moment — not just for the team, but for every girl kicking a ball in a dusty township street, daring to believe she could be a professional footballer. The investment is following: more academies, better facilities, and growing media coverage.</p>

<h2>Changing Perceptions</h2>
<p>Perhaps the most significant barrier being broken is perception. The tired argument that women's football is "less entertaining" has been obliterated by the quality on display. The technical ability, tactical sophistication, and competitive intensity of modern women's football rivals anything in the men's game. Different? Perhaps. Lesser? Absolutely not.</p>

<p>Five-a-side has played a crucial role in this revolution. Mixed-gender five-a-side leagues are thriving, creating spaces where skill matters more than physicality and where women and men compete as equals. These pitches are where stereotypes go to die.</p>

<h2>The Next Generation</h2>
<p>The most exciting part of this story is that it's only beginning. Today's ten-year-olds have never known a world without women's football on television. For them, seeing women play professionally isn't groundbreaking — it's normal. And that normalisation might be the biggest barrier-breaking achievement of all.</p>`
