    createdAt: "2026-02-25T07:30:00Z",
    views: 2100,
    content: `<p>Before the academies, before the stadiums, before the billion-dollar transfers — there were the streets. Every footballing great started the same way: a ball, a patch of ground, and an imagination. Street football is the soul of the sport, and around the world, it speaks a thousand different dialects of the same beautiful language.</p>

<h2>Brazil: The Cradle of Jogo Bonito</h2>
<p>In the favelas of Rio de Janeiro and the beaches of Copacabana, football is oxygen. Brazilian street football — futebol de rua — is where samba meets sport. The concrete courts are small, the surfaces unforgiving, and the skill level outrageous. Young players learn to play with a heavy futsal ball on hard surfaces, developing the close control and quick feet that define Brazilian football. Neymar, Ronaldinho, Rivaldo — all products of the street.</p>

<h2>Argentina: Potrero Football</h2>
<p>The potrero — a patch of wasteland or car park — is Argentina's football factory. The game is physical, competitive, and unapologetically aggressive. There are no coaches, no tactics boards, no substitutions. You learn to shield the ball because if you lose it, you might get kicked. Messi's preternatural ability to dribble through contact was forged not in Barcelona's La Masia, but on the rough patches of Rosario.</p>

<h2>South Africa: Kasi Football</h2>
<p>Township football — kasi ball — is theatre. The showboating isn't optional; it's the point. A simple pass when a rabona is available? Unacceptable. An orthodox dribble when you could do a rainbow flick? Never. Kasi football values entertainment above everything. The crowd reactions drive the creativity, and the creativity drives the culture. It's football as performance art.</p>

<h2>London: Cage Football</h2>
<p>In London's concrete cages, street football has its own flavour. The walls are in play, the teams are diverse, and the panna — nutmeg — is the ultimate humiliation. These cages have produced Premier League talent and created a thriving scene of YouTube channels, tournaments, and brands built entirely around small-sided street football.</p>

<p>Street football doesn't need investment, infrastructure, or institutions. It just needs people who love the game. That's why it will always be football's heartbeat — raw, real, and completely free.</p>`
