    createdAt: "2026-03-05T12:00:00Z",
    views: 1730,
    content: `<p>Football and fashion have always been intertwined, but the relationship has evolved from accidental to intentional. What started with fans wearing replica shirts has become a multi-billion dollar crossover where runway designers collaborate with football brands, and footballers are as famous for their wardrobes as their goals.</p>

<h2>The Jersey as Cultural Artefact</h2>
<p>A football jersey is never just a jersey. It carries identity, belonging, and memory. The AC Milan red and black stripes, Barcelona's blaugrana, the green and gold of South Africa — these colours trigger emotional responses that transcend fashion. Vintage football shirts have become collector's items, with rare kits from the 1990s selling for hundreds or even thousands of pounds.</p>

<p>The streetwear movement accelerated this trend. Brands like Nike, Adidas, and Puma began designing jerseys with off-pitch wearability in mind. Bold patterns, retro designs, and cultural references transformed the humble football shirt into a fashion statement. When you see someone wearing a 1994 Nigeria kit at a music festival, they might not even follow football — they just know it looks incredible.</p>

<h2>Footballer as Fashion Icon</h2>
<p>David Beckham was the pioneer, turning the tunnel walk into a catwalk. But today's footballers have taken it further. Héctor Bellerín models for fashion houses. Memphis Depay launched his own clothing line. Megan Rapinoe became a cultural icon whose influence extends far beyond the pitch. Footballers no longer just endorse fashion brands — they shape fashion culture.</p>

<h2>Five-a-Side Style</h2>
<p>The five-a-side fashion game is real. Custom team jerseys with creative names and numbers, colour-coordinated boots and bibs, the perfect pair of astro turf trainers — looking good while playing good is part of the culture. Some players invest more thought into their five-a-side outfit than their work wardrobe, and honestly? We respect it.</p>

<p>Football fashion reflects football's place in society — not just a sport, but a lifestyle. From the favelas to the fashion weeks, the beautiful game dresses beautifully.</p>`
