    id: 12,
    slug: "how-small-sided-games-improve-your-touch",
    title: "How Small-Sided Games Improve Your Touch",
    image: "/posts/blog12.jpg",
    category: "5-a-Side",
    tags: ["5-a-Side", "Skills", "Training", "Touch"],
    author: authors["Jackson Wayne"],
    readingTime: 5,
    createdAt: "2026-03-06T15:00:00Z",
    views: 1340,
    content: `<p>The first touch is football's great separator. It's the difference between a player who controls the game and one who's controlled by it. And the single most effective way to develop a world-class first touch isn't through drills or YouTube tutorials — it's through playing small-sided games regularly.</p>

<h2>The Numbers Don't Lie</h2>
<p>In a standard 11v11 match, an outfield player touches the ball approximately 50-60 times over ninety minutes. In a 5v5 game lasting sixty minutes, that same player touches the ball 200-300 times. That's five times more contact with the ball, five times more opportunities to receive, control, and distribute. Multiply that across weeks and months, and the compound effect on technical development is staggering.</p>

<h2>Pressure Creates Diamonds</h2>
<p>Small-sided games compress space and time. In eleven-a-side, you might have three seconds and five metres of space to control the ball. In five-a-side, you have one second and half a metre. This pressure forces players to develop what coaches call "pre-scanning" — checking their surroundings before receiving the ball so they can take a quality first touch in the right direction.</p>

<p>The best five-a-side players seem to have more time than everyone else. They don't — they just know where the pressure is coming from before the ball arrives. This awareness, combined with a technically proficient first touch, creates the illusion of time that separates elite players from average ones.</p>

<h2>Variety of Surfaces</h2>
<p>Five-a-side demands touches with every surface of the foot, often in quick succession. Inside, outside, sole, laces — the game requires a complete technical vocabulary. You might receive with the inside of your right foot, roll the ball with the sole, and pass with the outside of your left — all within two seconds. This variety builds a complete player.</p>

<h2>Practical Tips</h2>
<p>To maximise the touch-improvement benefits of five-a-side, play with intention. Before each game, set yourself a personal challenge: every first touch must go forward. Or: receive everything on your weaker foot. Or: no more than two touches before passing. These constraints accelerate learning by forcing you out of comfortable habits and into deliberate practice. Your touch will thank you within weeks.</p>`
