    slug: "fitness-tips-for-weekend-warriors",
    title: "Fitness Tips for Weekend Warriors",
    image: "/posts/blog15.jpg",
    category: "Fitness",
    tags: ["Fitness", "Health", "Training", "Recovery"],
    author: authors["Halley Watikise"],
    readingTime: 5,
    createdAt: "2026-03-09T14:30:00Z",
    views: 1680,
    content: `<p>You haven't run all week. You've eaten questionable things. Sleep was optional. But it's match day, and for the next sixty minutes, you're going to sprint, tackle, shoot, and celebrate like your life depends on it. Welcome to the weekend warrior lifestyle — where ambition consistently outpaces preparation. Here's how to survive it.</p>

<h2>Pre-Game: The Hour That Saves You</h2>
<p>Arriving at the pitch cold is the weekend warrior's greatest sin. Your muscles are tight from sitting at a desk all week, your joints are stiff, and your body is completely unprepared for the explosive movements you're about to demand from it. Ten minutes of dynamic stretching — leg swings, hip circles, high knees, and light jogging — dramatically reduces injury risk and improves performance.</p>

<p>Hydration starts before you arrive. Drink at least 500ml of water in the hour before kickoff. Dehydration reduces reaction time, increases fatigue, and makes you more susceptible to muscle cramps. That pulled hamstring in the last five minutes? Probably dehydration, not bad luck.</p>

<h2>During the Game: Play Smart</h2>
<p>The temptation to sprint everywhere for the full sixty minutes is strong. Resist it. Even professional footballers only sprint for 1-2% of a match. The rest is jogging, walking, and intelligent positioning. Conserve your energy for the moments that matter — the counter-attack, the defensive recovery, the goal-scoring opportunity. Playing smart beats playing hard.</p>

<h2>Post-Game: Recovery Is Not Optional</h2>
<p>The game ends and you head straight to the car or the bar. Your muscles are screaming. Tomorrow, stairs will be your nemesis. This is entirely preventable. Five minutes of static stretching after the game — hamstrings, quads, calves, hip flexors — costs nothing and saves days of pain. Follow up with protein within an hour (a shake, chicken, even chocolate milk) to kickstart muscle repair.</p>

<h2>Between Games: The Minimum Effective Dose</h2>
<p>You don't need a gym membership or a personal trainer. Two twenty-minute sessions per week — one focused on lower body strength (squats, lunges, calf raises) and one on cardio (a brisk walk, cycle, or light jog) — will transform your matchday performance. Your teammates will wonder what happened. Your body will thank you. And that hamstring? It'll stay intact.</p>`
