    author: authors["Jackson Wayne"],
    readingTime: 5,
    createdAt: "2026-03-18T08:30:00Z",
    views: 1380,
    content: `<p>The goalkeeper is football's loneliest position. One mistake erases ninety minutes of perfection. One moment of brilliance saves a season. In five-a-side, the goalkeeper's role is amplified — you face more shots, make more saves, and have a greater influence on the outcome than any outfield player.</p>

<h2>Positioning: The Art of Narrowing Angles</h2>
<p>The best goalkeepers make saves before the shot is taken — through positioning. By understanding angles, a goalkeeper can make a goal that's 7.32 metres wide appear to the striker as if it's barely a metre. The principle is simple: come off your line to narrow the angle, but don't come so far that you can be chipped. In five-a-side, where the goals are smaller, this balance is even more critical.</p>

<p>Stand on the imaginary line between the ball and the centre of the goal. As the ball moves, you move. This basic principle, executed consistently, eliminates 70% of shots before they're even taken. The other 30% require reflexes, courage, and technique.</p>

<h2>The Ready Position</h2>
<p>Your stance determines your reaction time. Feet shoulder-width apart, weight on the balls of your feet, knees slightly bent, hands by your sides at waist height, and eyes locked on the ball. This "set position" should be held every time a shot is possible. Goalkeepers who stand upright, flat-footed, or with their hands too high are adding milliseconds to their reaction time — and in goalkeeping, milliseconds are the difference between hero and villain.</p>

<h2>Distribution</h2>
<p>The modern goalkeeper — especially in five-a-side — starts attacks. A quick, accurate throw to an unmarked teammate is worth more than any spectacular save. Practice rolling the ball to feet with pace and precision. Develop your kicking ability with both feet. In five-a-side, the goalkeeper often has the best view of the pitch and the most time on the ball. Use both wisely.</p>

<h2>The Mental Game</h2>
<p>Goalkeeping requires a short memory. You will concede goals that are entirely your fault. You will make errors that cost your team. The ability to immediately forget and refocus is the single most important goalkeeper skill. The best keepers in the world make mistakes — they just never make the same mistake twice in one game.</p>`
