    content: `<p>Football's greatest strength isn't tactics, talent, or tradition — it's diversity. The sport thrives because it belongs to everyone, regardless of race, religion, gender, nationality, or background. This diversity isn't just worth celebrating — it's the very foundation upon which football's global appeal is built.</p>

<h2>The Universal Language</h2>
<p>A ball needs no translation. On any pitch, in any country, two strangers can communicate through football without sharing a single word of the same language. A pass, a nod, a thumbs up — the sport creates its own vocabulary of connection. This universal accessibility is why football is the world's most popular sport, played in every nation on earth, from the frozen pitches of Iceland to the dusty fields of rural Africa.</p>

<p>Five-a-side football amplifies this diversity beautifully. In any major city, a typical five-a-side game might feature players from five different countries, speaking three different languages, united by their love of the game. The pitch is a melting pot where cultural differences become strengths — the Brazilian's flair, the German's discipline, the South African's showmanship, the Japanese player's precision.</p>

<h2>Breaking Down Barriers</h2>
<p>Football has been a vehicle for social change throughout its history. Jackie Robinson broke baseball's colour barrier, but football has its own pioneers. Viv Anderson became England's first Black international in 1978. Lily Parr scored over 900 goals for Dick, Kerr's Ladies in an era when women's football was banned. These trailblazers didn't just play the game — they changed society through it.</p>

<h2>The Work That Remains</h2>
<p>Celebration shouldn't mean complacency. Racism in football stadiums persists. Women's football still receives a fraction of men's investment. LGBTQ+ players remain largely invisible in the professional game. Disability football deserves more visibility and funding. The journey toward true equality in football is ongoing, and every player, fan, and administrator has a role to play.</p>

<p>But the direction of travel is clear: football is becoming more inclusive, more diverse, and more representative of the world it serves. And the game is immeasurably better for it.</p>`
