    views: 5100,
    content: `<p>GOOOOOAL! That one word, screamed in every language on earth, is the reason football exists. The ball hitting the net is football's moment of pure ecstasy — the payoff for ninety minutes of effort, the validation of a team's strategy, and the trigger for the most primal celebration in all of sport. But behind every goal lies technique, timing, and an instinct that can be developed.</p>

<h2>The Instinct of a Scorer</h2>
<p>Great goal scorers see things differently. While other players see defenders, the scorer sees gaps. While others see pressure, the scorer sees opportunity. This "goal sense" — the ability to anticipate where the ball will land, to find the right position before the chance materialises — is partly innate and partly trained. Players like Gerd Müller, Filippo Inzaghi, and Cristiano Ronaldo possessed it in abundance. They scored goals that seemed inevitable because they were already in the right place when the opportunity arrived.</p>

<h2>Finishing Technique</h2>
<p>Power versus placement is the eternal debate. The answer? It depends. From close range, placement wins every time — a side-footed finish into the corner gives the goalkeeper no chance. From distance, controlled power is key — enough pace to beat the keeper's reactions, enough accuracy to hit the target. The worst option is always the panicked blast that flies into row Z.</p>

<p>The best drill for finishing is brutally simple: shoot from different positions, different angles, and different distances. Right foot, left foot, header. Moving ball, bouncing ball, ball in the air. Repetition builds muscle memory, and muscle memory removes hesitation. When the chance comes in a match, you don't think — you execute.</p>

<h2>Five-a-Side Finishing</h2>
<p>In five-a-side, the distances are shorter and the margins are tighter. The most effective finishing technique is the low, hard shot across the goalkeeper. Keepers in five-a-side tend to go down late, so a shot driven firmly into the bottom corner — especially the far post — is the highest-percentage option. Don't overthink it. Hit the target. Hit it early. Hit it low. GOOOOOAL!</p>`
